<paragraph blockId="5.[150,1438,404,1977]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The names for the Order 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1836" box="[433,585,439,464]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Thysanoptera</taxonomicName>
and its two suborders date from 
<bibRefCitation author="Haliday, A. H." box="[954,1127,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="439 - 451" refId="ref60837" refString="Haliday, A. H. (1836) An epitome of the British genera in the Order Thysanoptera with indications of a few of the species. Entomological Magazine, 3, 439 - 451." type="journal article" year="1836">Haliday (1836)</bibRefCitation>
. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Uzel, H." box="[1302,1436,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 472" refId="ref65455" refString="Uzel, H. (1895) Monographie der Ordnung Thysanoptera. Konigratz, Bohemia. Pp 1 - 472." type="book chapter" year="1895">Uzel (1895)</bibRefCitation>
produced the major work that provided the basis for future studies on these insects, and recognised 
<taxonomicName box="[1260,1436,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phlaeothripidae</taxonomicName>
as the single family of 
<taxonomicName box="[412,532,511,536]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subOrder" subOrder="Tubulifera">Tubulifera</taxonomicName>
, to which 
<bibRefCitation author="Bagnall, R. S." box="[650,819,511,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="183 - 217" refId="ref59594" refString="Bagnall, R. S. (1908) On some new genera and species of Thysanoptera. Transactions of the Natural History Society of Northumberland, 3, 183 - 217." type="journal article" year="1908">Bagnall (1908)</bibRefCitation>
later added the Idolothripidae as a second family. The subfamily sense in which these two names are now used derives from 
<bibRefCitation author="Stannard, L. J." box="[1023,1213,548,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 200" refId="ref64986" refString="Stannard, L. J. (1957) The phylogeny and classification of the North American genera of the sub-order Tubulifera (Thysanoptera). Illinois Biological Monographs, 25, 1 - 200." type="journal article" year="1957">Stannard (1957)</bibRefCitation>
, although he used Megathripinae, a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1908" box="[562,721,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Idolothripinae">Idolothripinae</taxonomicName>
that was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Karny, H." box="[951,1107,583,608]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 126" refId="ref61531" refString="Karny, H. (1913) Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Gallen von Java 5. Uber die javanischen Thysanopteren-cecidien und deren Bewohner. Bulletin du Jardin Botanique de Buitenzorg, 10, 1 - 126." type="journal article" year="1913">Karny (1913)</bibRefCitation>
. The classification within the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,327,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phlaeothripidae</taxonomicName>
proposed by Stannard attempted to recognise phylogenetic relationships. In contrast, the classification proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Priesner, H." box="[454,629,655,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="283 - 296" refId="ref64620" refString="Priesner, H. (1961) Das System der Tubulifera (Thysanoptera). Anzeiger mathematisch-naturwissenschaftliche Klasse, Osterreichische Akademie der Wissenschaften, [1960] 13, 283 - 296." type="journal article" year="1961">Priesner (1961)</bibRefCitation>
was essentially typological, with many group names provided for taxa exhibiting some unusual character state. A particularly unfortunate decision in that classification was to place 
<taxonomicName box="[151,286,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,286,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Hoplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a major genus of fungus-feeding species, in the same group as the many genera of leaf-feeding species related to 
<taxonomicName box="[364,467,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Liothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[364,467,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Liothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This is particularly relevant here, because 
<bibRefCitation author="Han, Y. F." box="[987,1122,764,789]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="ref60924" refString="Han, Y. F. (1997) Economic Insect Fauna of China. 55 Thysanoptera. Editorial Committee of Fauna Sinica, Science Press, Beijing, 514 pp." type="book" year="1997">Han (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, in the only review of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1836" box="[151,303,799,824]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Thysanoptera</taxonomicName>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[341,410,799,824]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">China</collectingCountry>
, adopted the Priesner typological classification. One major objective of the work presented here is to draw to the attention of thrips students in 
<collectingCountry box="[746,813,836,861]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">China</collectingCountry>
and Southeast Asia a more modern approach to thrips phylogenetic relationships, and to emphasise that most of the suprageneric names in Han and Priesner are no longer used.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[150,1438,404,1977]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The various names proposed for supra-generic taxa now placed in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1908" box="[1000,1163,943,968]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Idolothripinae">Idolothripinae</taxonomicName>
have been discussed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Palmer, J. M." box="[150,475,980,1005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 174" refId="ref62895" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Palmer, J. M. (1983 a) The generic and tribal classification of spore-feeding Thysanoptera (Phlaeothripidae: Idolothripinae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology, 46, 1 - 174." type="journal article" year="1983">Mound and Palmer (1983a)</bibRefCitation>
. The following comments refer to the names available within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Uzel" authorityYear="1895" box="[1249,1433,980,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phlaeothripinae">Phlaeothripinae</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Stannard, L. J." box="[153,343,1015,1040]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 200" refId="ref64986" refString="Stannard, L. J. (1957) The phylogeny and classification of the North American genera of the sub-order Tubulifera (Thysanoptera). Illinois Biological Monographs, 25, 1 - 200." type="journal article" year="1957">Stannard (1957)</bibRefCitation>
recognized the following as representing nine major lineages within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Uzel" authorityYear="1895" box="[1250,1434,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phlaeothripinae">Phlaeothripinae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[151,289,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Haplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,289,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Haplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName box="[306,466,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Gigantothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[306,466,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Gigantothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buffa" authorityYear="1909" box="[484,676,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Amphibolothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[484,676,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Amphibolothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName box="[694,838,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hyidiothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[694,838,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Hyidiothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName box="[855,1005,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Plectrothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[855,1005,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Plectrothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1908" box="[1022,1259,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Docessissophothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1022,1259,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Docessissophothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName box="[1276,1427,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Williamsiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1276,1427,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Williamsiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1924" box="[151,288,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Neurothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,288,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Neurothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1912" box="[355,500,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Glyptothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[355,500,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Glyptothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R." box="[516,834,1087,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 488" refId="ref62764" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R. (1996) The Thrips of Central and South America: An Introduction. Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">Mound and Marullo (1996)</bibRefCitation>
built on the ideas of Stannard, but recognized only three major lineages. The first was Stannard’s 
<taxonomicName box="[685,823,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Haplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[685,823,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Haplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-lineage and this was subsequently treated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Minaei, K." pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="2919 - 2978" refId="ref62801" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Minaei, K. (2007) Australian insects of the Haplothrips lineage (Thysanoptera - Phlaeothripinae). Journal of Natural History, 41 (45 - 48), 2919 - 2978. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930701783219" type="journal article" year="2007">Mound and Minaei (2007)</bibRefCitation>
as the Tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[524,678,1159,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Haplothripini">Haplothripini</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation box="[695,782,1159,1184]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetId="graphics-384@6.[150,1436,257,2029]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. List of Phlaeothripinae genera discussed in this paper [Number of described species in parentheses—see ThripsWiki 2014] [Austrothrips—see main text; Chalepothrips Priesner 1968: 191—name invalid]" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/96CC6667665A47282BFAFF34C0F5FF6F" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" tableUuid="96CC6667665A47282BFAFF34C0F5FF6F">Table 1</tableCitation>
), a group of flower-feeders that also includes genera of predatory species. The second major group recognised by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R." box="[836,1156,1196,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 488" refId="ref62764" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R. (1996) The Thrips of Central and South America: An Introduction. Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">Mound and Marullo (1996)</bibRefCitation>
is the 
<taxonomicName box="[1238,1343,1196,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Liothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1238,1343,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Liothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-lineage that includes most of the leaf-feeding 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Uzel" authorityYear="1895" box="[590,770,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phlaeothripinae">Phlaeothripinae</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation box="[785,872,1231,1256]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetId="graphics-384@6.[150,1436,257,2029]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. List of Phlaeothripinae genera discussed in this paper [Number of described species in parentheses—see ThripsWiki 2014] [Austrothrips—see main text; Chalepothrips Priesner 1968: 191—name invalid]" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/96CC6667665A47282BFAFF34C0F5FF6F" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" tableUuid="96CC6667665A47282BFAFF34C0F5FF6F">Table 1</tableCitation>
), and this corresponds to the group discussed by Stannard as the 
<taxonomicName box="[336,496,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Gigantothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[336,496,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Gigantothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
line. The third major group is the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halliday" authorityYear="1836" box="[899,1047,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Phlaeothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[899,1047,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Phlaeothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-lineage of species most of which feed on fungal hyphae, and this comprises the remaining seven groups recognized by Stannard (
<tableCitation box="[1328,1420,1303,1328]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetId="graphics-384@6.[150,1436,257,2029]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. List of Phlaeothripinae genera discussed in this paper [Number of described species in parentheses—see ThripsWiki 2014] [Austrothrips—see main text; Chalepothrips Priesner 1968: 191—name invalid]" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/96CC6667665A47282BFAFF34C0F5FF6F" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" tableUuid="96CC6667665A47282BFAFF34C0F5FF6F">Table 1</tableCitation>
). Amongst this large assemblage, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buffa" authorityYear="1909" box="[574,766,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Amphibolothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[574,766,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Amphibolothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus-group is sometimes referred to as the urothripines (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A." box="[161,314,1375,1400]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="83 - 103" refId="ref62199" refString="Mound, L. A. (1972) Species complexes and the generic classification of leaf-litter thrips of the Tribe Urothripini (Phlaeothripidae). Australian Journal of Zoology, 20, 83 - 103. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1071 / zo 9720083" type="journal article" year="1972">Mound 1972</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ulitzka, M. R. &amp; Mound, L. A." box="[328,605,1375,1400]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="595 - 600" refId="ref65394" refString="Ulitzka, M. R. &amp; Mound, L. A. (2014) New generic synonyms in the Palaeotropical genus Urothrips (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripinae) with one new species from Seychelles. Zootaxa, 3755 (6), 595 - 600. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3755.6.6" type="journal article" year="2014">Ulitzka &amp; Mound 2014</bibRefCitation>
); these are small species that commonly live in leaf-litter, and have the tube and ninth abdominal tergite particularly elongate. Members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[996,1141,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hyidiothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[996,1141,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Hyidiothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus-group are minute, pale and laterally flattened species. Although generally found in leaf-litter where they are presumed to be fungus-feeders (
<bibRefCitation author="Okajima, S." box="[340,513,1484,1509]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="ref64063" refString="Okajima, S. (2006) The Insects of Japan. Vol. 2. The suborder Tubulifera (Thysanoptera). Touka Shobo Co Ltd., Fukuoka, 720 pp." type="book" year="2006">Okajima 2006</bibRefCitation>
), in 
<collectingCountry box="[571,676,1484,1509]" name="Australia" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Australia</collectingCountry>
one species has been found on the leaves of 
<taxonomicName box="[1232,1327,1485,1508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Lantana" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1232,1327,1485,1508]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Lantana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
where it appears to be predatory on mites. Species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[704,854,1519,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Plectrothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[704,854,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Plectrothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus-group are fungus-feeders on dead branches, and have the sensorium on the second antennal segment placed on the basal half of that segment (
<bibRefCitation author="Okajima, S." pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="291 - 336" refId="ref63393" refString="Okajima, S. (1981) A revision of the tribe Plectrothripini of fungus-feeding Thysanoptera (Phlaeothripidae: Phlaeothripinae). Systematic Entomology, 6, 291 - 336. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1981. tb 00441. x" type="journal article" year="1981">Okajima 1981</bibRefCitation>
). The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1908" box="[289,526,1591,1616]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Docessissophothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[289,526,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Docessissophothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus-group includes fungus-feeding species with unusually broad maxillary stylets that are often greatly elongate, and most of these species are placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1167,1291,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1167,1291,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Holothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In contrast, the 
<taxonomicName box="[195,346,1663,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Williamsiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[195,346,1663,1688]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Williamsiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus-group involves species in which the stylets are sometimes very short, and these thrips are associated with mosses (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A." box="[482,636,1700,1725]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 17" refId="ref62297" refString="Mound, L. A. (1989) Systematics of thrips (Insecta: Thysanoptera) associated with mosses. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 96, 1 - 17. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1989. tb 01818. x" type="journal article" year="1989">Mound 1989</bibRefCitation>
). The final two groups recognized by Stannard, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1924" box="[1248,1385,1700,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Neurothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1248,1385,1700,1725]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Neurothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1912" box="[151,296,1735,1760]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Glyptothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,296,1735,1760]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Glyptothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lines, include most of the genera of fungus-feeding species found on dead branches and in leaf litter, including 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halliday" authorityYear="1836" box="[336,483,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Phlaeothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[336,483,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Phlaeothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[499,637,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[499,637,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Hoplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[652,817,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Adraneothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[652,817,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Adraneothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[882,1073,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplandrothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[882,1073,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Hoplandrothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1912" box="[1140,1285,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Glyptothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1140,1285,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Glyptothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus-group has been used for taxa with prominent reticulation on the head, but that condition is now recognised as highly variable within some genera (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A." box="[489,642,1844,1869]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="209 - 215" refId="ref62352" refString="Mound, L. A. (2002) Zemiathrips; a new genus of fungus-feeding phlaeothripine Thysanoptera in Australian leaf-litter. Australian Journal of Entomology, 41, 209 - 215. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1440 - 6055.2002.00296. x" type="journal article" year="2002">Mound 2002</bibRefCitation>
). The suprageneric classification of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Uzel" authorityYear="1895" box="[1055,1235,1844,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phlaeothripinae">Phlaeothripinae</taxonomicName>
remains less than satisfactory. Two reasonably well-defined major groups can be distinguished, the 
<taxonomicName box="[1173,1327,1879,1904]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Haplothripini">Haplothripini</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,256,1916,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Liothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,256,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Liothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-lineage. But the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halliday" authorityYear="1836" box="[466,614,1916,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Phlaeothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[466,614,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Phlaeothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-lineage of fungus-feeding species is clearly a complex, polyphyletic assemblage (
<bibRefCitation author="Buckman, R. S. &amp; Mound, L. A. &amp; Whiting, M. F." box="[298,543,1952,1977]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="123 - 133" refId="ref60082" refString="Buckman, R. S., Mound, L. A. &amp; Whiting, M. F. (2013) Phylogeny of thrips (Insecta: Thysanoptera) based on five molecular loci. Systematic Entomology, 38, 123 - 133. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2012.00650. x" type="journal article" year="2013">
Buckman 
<emphasis box="[416,466,1952,1977]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
